en_name: Teenage mothers (% of women ages 15-19 who have had children or are currently pregnant)
en_description: Teenage mothers are the percentage of women ages 15-19 who already have children or are currently pregnant.

en_name: Women who were first married by age 18 (% of women ages 20-24)
en_description: Women who were first married by age 18 refers to the percentage of women ages 20-24 who were first married by age 18.

en_name: Women who were first married by age 15 (% of women ages 20-24)
en_description: Women who were first married by age 15 refers to the percentage of women ages 20-24 who were first married by age 15.

en_name: Female headed households (% of households with a female head)
en_description: Female headed households shows the percentage of households with a female head.

en_name: Wanted fertility rate (births per woman)
en_description: Wanted fertility rate is an estimate of what the total fertility rate would be if all unwanted births were avoided.

en_name: Survival to age 65, male (% of cohort)
en_description: Survival to age 65 refers to the percentage of a cohort of newborn infants that would survive to age 65, if subject to age specific mortality rates of the specified year.

en_name: Survival to age 65, female (% of cohort)
en_description: Survival to age 65 refers to the percentage of a cohort of newborn infants that would survive to age 65, if subject to age specific mortality rates of the specified year.

en_name: Fertility rate, total (births per woman)
en_description: Total fertility rate represents the number of children that would be born to a woman if she were to live to the end of her childbearing years and bear children in accordance with age-specific fertility rates of the specified year.

en_name: Life expectancy at birth, male (years)
en_description: Life expectancy at birth indicates the number of years a newborn infant would live if prevailing patterns of mortality at the time of its birth were to stay the same throughout its life.

en_name: Life expectancy at birth, female (years)
en_description: Life expectancy at birth indicates the number of years a newborn infant would live if prevailing patterns of mortality at the time of its birth were to stay the same throughout its life.

en_name: Mortality rate, adult, male (per 1,000 male adults)
en_description: Adult mortality rate, male, is the probability of dying between the ages of 15 and 60--that is, the probability of a 15-year-old male dying before reaching age 60, if subject to age-specific mortality rates of the specified year between those ages.

en_name: Mortality rate, adult, female (per 1,000 female adults)
en_description: Adult mortality rate, female, is the probability of dying between the ages of 15 and 60--that is, the probability of a 15-year-old female dying before reaching age 60, if subject to age-specific mortality rates of the specified year between those ages.

en_name: Adolescent fertility rate (births per 1,000 women ages 15-19)
en_description: Adolescent fertility rate is the number of births per 1,000 women ages 15-19.

en_name: Unemployment, male (% of male labor force) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Unemployment refers to the share of the labor force that is without work but available for and seeking employment.

en_name: Unemployment, female (% of female labor force) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Unemployment refers to the share of the labor force that is without work but available for and seeking employment.

en_name: Unemployment, youth male (% of male labor force ages 15-24) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Youth unemployment refers to the share of the labor force ages 15-24 without work but available for and seeking employment.

en_name: Unemployment, youth female (% of female labor force ages 15-24) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Youth unemployment refers to the share of the labor force ages 15-24 without work but available for and seeking employment.

en_name: Labor force, female (% of total labor force)
en_description: Female labor force as a percentage of the total show the extent to which women are active in the labor force. Labor force comprises people ages 15 and older who supply labor for the production of goods and services during a specified period.

en_name: Part time employment, male (% of total male employment)
en_description: Part time employment refers to regular employment in which working time is substantially less than normal. Definitions of part time employment differ by country.

en_name: Part time employment, female (% of total female employment)
en_description: Part time employment refers to regular employment in which working time is substantially less than normal. Definitions of part time employment differ by country.

en_name: Labor force participation rate, male (% of male population ages 15+) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Labor force participation rate is the proportion of the population ages 15 and older that is economically active: all people who supply labor for the production of goods and services during a specified period.

en_name: Labor force participation rate, female (% of female population ages 15+) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Labor force participation rate is the proportion of the population ages 15 and older that is economically active: all people who supply labor for the production of goods and services during a specified period.

en_name: Children in employment, work only, male (% of male children in employment, ages 7-14)
en_description: Children in employment refer to children involved in economic activity for at least one hour in the reference week of the survey. Work only refers to children involved in economic activity and not attending school.

en_name: Children in employment, work only, female (% of female children in employment, ages 7-14)
en_description: Children in employment refer to children involved in economic activity for at least one hour in the reference week of the survey. Work only refers to children involved in economic activity and not attending school.

en_name: Children in employment, study and work, male (% of male children in employment, ages 7-14)
en_description: Children in employment refer to children involved in economic activity for at least one hour in the reference week of the survey. Study and work refer to children attending school in combination with economic activity.

en_name: Children in employment, study and work, female (% of female children in employment, ages 7-14)
en_description: Children in employment refer to children involved in economic activity for at least one hour in the reference week of the survey. Study and work refer to children attending school in combination with economic activity.

en_name: Children in employment, male (% of male children ages 7-14)
en_description: Children in employment refer to children involved in economic activity for at least one hour in the reference week of the survey.

en_name: Children in employment, female (% of female children ages 7-14)
en_description: Children in employment refer to children involved in economic activity for at least one hour in the reference week of the survey.

en_name: Child employment in manufacturing, male (% of male economically active children ages 7-14)
en_description: Employment by economic activity refers to the distribution of economically active children by the major industrial categories of the International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC). Manufacturing corresponds to division 3 (ISIC revision 2), category D (ISIC revision 3), or category C (ISIC revision 4). Economically active children refer to children involved in economic activity for at least one hour in the reference week of the survey.

en_name: Child employment in manufacturing, female (% of female economically active children ages 7-14)
en_description: Employment by economic activity refers to the distribution of economically active children by the major industrial categories of the International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC). Manufacturing corresponds to division 3 (ISIC revision 2), category D (ISIC revision 3), or category C (ISIC revision 4). Economically active children refer to children involved in economic activity for at least one hour in the reference week of the survey.

en_name: Employment in industry, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Employment is defined as persons of working age who were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangement. The industry sector consists of mining and quarrying, manufacturing, construction, and public utilities (electricity, gas, and water), in accordance with divisions 2-5 (ISIC 2) or categories C-F (ISIC 3) or categories B-F (ISIC 4).

en_name: Employment in industry, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Employment is defined as persons of working age who were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangement. The industry sector consists of mining and quarrying, manufacturing, construction, and public utilities (electricity, gas, and water), in accordance with divisions 2-5 (ISIC 2) or categories C-F (ISIC 3) or categories B-F (ISIC 4).

en_name: Contributing family workers, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Contributing family workers are those workers who hold "self-employment jobs" as own-account workers in a market-oriented establishment operated by a related person living in the same household.

en_name: Contributing family workers, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Contributing family workers are those workers who hold "self-employment jobs" as own-account workers in a market-oriented establishment operated by a related person living in the same household.

en_name: Wage and salaried workers, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Wage and salaried workers (employees) are those workers who hold the type of jobs defined as "paid employment jobs

en_name: Wage and salaried workers, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Wage and salaried workers (employees) are those workers who hold the type of jobs defined as "paid employment jobs

en_name: Vulnerable employment, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Vulnerable employment is contributing family workers and own-account workers as a percentage of total employment.

en_name: Vulnerable employment, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Vulnerable employment is contributing family workers and own-account workers as a percentage of total employment.

en_name: Self-employed, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Self-employed workers are those workers who, working on their own account or with one or a few partners or in cooperative, hold the type of jobs defined as a "self-employment jobs."" i.e. jobs where the remuneration is directly dependent upon the profits derived from the goods and services produced. Self-employed workers include four sub-categories of employers

en_name: Self-employed, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Self-employed workers are those workers who, working on their own account or with one or a few partners or in cooperative, hold the type of jobs defined as a "self-employment jobs."" i.e. jobs where the remuneration is directly dependent upon the profits derived from the goods and services produced. Self-employed workers include four sub-categories of employers

en_name: Employers, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Employers are those workers who, working on their own account or with one or a few partners, hold the type of jobs defined as a "self-employment jobs"" i.e. jobs where the remuneration is directly dependent upon the profits derived from the goods and services produced)

en_name: Employers, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Employers are those workers who, working on their own account or with one or a few partners, hold the type of jobs defined as a "self-employment jobs"" i.e. jobs where the remuneration is directly dependent upon the profits derived from the goods and services produced)

en_name: Employment to population ratio, ages 15-24, male (%) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Employment to population ratio is the proportion of a country's population that is employed. Employment is defined as persons of working age who, during a short reference period, were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period (i.e. who worked in a job for at least one hour) or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangements. Ages 15-24 are generally considered the youth population.

en_name: Employment to population ratio, ages 15-24, female (%) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Employment to population ratio is the proportion of a country's population that is employed. Employment is defined as persons of working age who, during a short reference period, were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period (i.e. who worked in a job for at least one hour) or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangements. Ages 15-24 are generally considered the youth population.

en_name: Employment in agriculture, male (% of male employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Employment is defined as persons of working age who were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangement. The agriculture sector consists of activities in agriculture, hunting, forestry and fishing, in accordance with division 1 (ISIC 2) or categories A-B (ISIC 3) or category A (ISIC 4).

en_name: Employment in agriculture, female (% of female employment) (modeled ILO estimate)
en_description: Employment is defined as persons of working age who were engaged in any activity to produce goods or provide services for pay or profit, whether at work during the reference period or not at work due to temporary absence from a job, or to working-time arrangement. The agriculture sector consists of activities in agriculture, hunting, forestry and fishing, in accordance with division 1 (ISIC 2) or categories A-B (ISIC 3) or category A (ISIC 4).

en_name: Child employment in agriculture, male (% of male economically active children ages 7-14)
en_description: Employment by economic activity refers to the distribution of economically active children by the major industrial categories of the International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC). Agriculture corresponds to division 1 (ISIC revision 2), categories A and B (ISIC revision 3), or category A (ISIC revision 4) and includes hunting, forestry, and fishing. Economically active children refer to children involved in economic activity for at least one hour in the reference week of the survey.

en_name: Child employment in agriculture, female (% of female economically active children ages 7-14)
en_description: Employment by economic activity refers to the distribution of economically active children by the major industrial categories of the International Standard Industrial Classification (ISIC). Agriculture corresponds to division 1 (ISIC revision 2), categories A and B (ISIC revision 3), or category A (ISIC revision 4) and includes hunting, forestry, and fishing. Economically active children refer to children involved in economic activity for at least one hour in the reference week of the survey.

en_name: Maternal mortality ratio (national estimate, per 100,000 live births)
en_description: Maternal mortality ratio is the number of women who die from pregnancy-related causes while pregnant or within 42 days of pregnancy termination per 100,000 live births.

en_name: Maternal mortality ratio (modeled estimate, per 100,000 live births)
en_description: Maternal mortality ratio is the number of women who die from pregnancy-related causes while pregnant or within 42 days of pregnancy termination per 100,000 live births. The data are estimated with a regression model using information on the proportion of maternal deaths among non-AIDS deaths in women ages 15-49, fertility, birth attendants, and GDP measured using purchasing power parities (PPPs).

en_name: Prevalence of underweight, weight for age, male (% of children under 5)
en_description: Prevalence of underweight, male, is the percentage of boys under age 5 whose weight for age is more than two standard deviations below the median for the international reference population ages 0-59 months. The data are based on the WHO's 2006 Child Growth Standards.

en_name: Prevalence of underweight, weight for age, female (% of children under 5)
en_description: Prevalence of underweight, female, is the percentage of girls under age 5 whose weight for age is more than two standard deviations below the median for the international reference population ages 0-59 months. The data are based on the WHO's 2006 Child Growth Standards.

en_name: Births attended by skilled health staff (% of total)
en_description: Births attended by skilled health staff are the percentage of deliveries attended by personnel trained to give the necessary supervision, care, and advice to women during pregnancy, labor, and the postpartum period; to conduct deliveries on their own; and to care for newborns.

en_name: Pregnant women receiving prenatal care (%)
en_description: Pregnant women receiving prenatal care are the percentage of women attended at least once during pregnancy by skilled health personnel for reasons related to pregnancy.

en_name: Lifetime risk of maternal death (%)
en_description: Life time risk of maternal death is the probability that a 15-year-old female will die eventually from a maternal cause assuming that current levels of fertility and mortality (including maternal mortality) do not change in the future, taking into account competing causes of death.

en_name: Lifetime risk of maternal death (1 in: rate varies by country)
en_description: Life time risk of maternal death is the probability that a 15-year-old female will die eventually from a maternal cause assuming that current levels of fertility and mortality (including maternal mortality) do not change in the future, taking into account competing causes of death.

en_name: Prevalence of HIV, male (% ages 15-24)
en_description: Prevalence of HIV, male is the percentage of males who are infected with HIV. Youth rates are as a percentage of the relevant age group.

en_name: Prevalence of HIV, female (% ages 15-24)
en_description: Prevalence of HIV, female is the percentage of females who are infected with HIV. Youth rates are as a percentage of the relevant age group.

en_name: Women's share of population ages 15+ living with HIV (%)
en_description: Prevalence of HIV is the percentage of people who are infected with HIV. Female rate is as a percentage of the total population ages 15+ who are living with HIV.

en_name: Condom use, population ages 15-24, male (% of males ages 15-24)
en_description: Condom use, male is the percentage of the male population ages 15-24 who used a condom at last intercourse in the last 12 months.

en_name: Condom use, population ages 15-24, female (% of females ages 15-24)
en_description: Condom use, female is the percentage of the female population ages 15-24 who used a condom at last intercourse in the last 12 months.

en_name: Women who believe a husband is justified in beating his wife when she refuses sex with him (%)
en_description: Percentage of women ages 15-49 who believe a husband/partner is justified in hitting or beating his wife/partner when she refuses sex with him.

en_name: Women who believe a husband is justified in beating his wife (any of five reasons) (%)
en_description: Percentage of women ages 15-49 who believe a husband/partner is justified in hitting or beating his wife/partner for any of the following five reasons: argues with him; refuses to have sex; burns the food; goes out without telling him; or when she neglects the children.

en_name: Women who believe a husband is justified in beating his wife when she neglects the children (%)
en_description: Percentage of women ages 15-49 who believe a husband/partner is justified in hitting or beating his wife/partner when she neglects the children.

en_name: Women who believe a husband is justified in beating his wife when she goes out without telling him (%)
en_description: Percentage of women ages 15-49 who believe a husband/partner is justified in hitting or beating his wife/partner when she goes out without telling him.

en_name: Women who believe a husband is justified in beating his wife when she burns the food (%)
en_description: Percentage of women ages 15-49 who believe a husband/partner is justified in hitting or beating his wife/partner when she burns the food.

en_name: Women who believe a husband is justified in beating his wife when she argues with him (%)
en_description: Percentage of women ages 15-49 who believe a husband/partner is justified in hitting or beating his wife/partner when she argues with him.

en_name: Proportion of women subjected to physical and/or sexual violence in the last 12 months (% of ever-partnered women ages 15-49)
en_description: Proportion of women subjected to physical and/or sexual violence in the last 12 months is the percentage of ever partnered women age 15-49 who are subjected to physical violence, sexual violence or both by a current or former intimate partner in the last 12 months.

en_name: Proportion of time spent on unpaid domestic and care work, male (% of 24 hour day)
en_description: The average time men spend on household provision of services for own consumption.  Data are expressed as a proportion of time in a day. Domestic and care work includes food preparation, dishwashing, cleaning and upkeep of a dwelling, laundry, ironing, gardening, caring for pets, shopping, installation, servicing and repair of personal and household goods, childcare, and care of the sick, elderly or disabled household members, among others.

en_name: Proportion of time spent on unpaid domestic and care work, female (% of 24 hour day)
en_description: The average time women spend on household provision of services for own consumption. Data are expressed as a proportion of time in a day. Domestic and care work includes food preparation, dishwashing, cleaning and upkeep of a dwelling, laundry, ironing, gardening, caring for pets, shopping, installation, servicing and repair of personal and household goods, childcare, and care of the sick, elderly or disabled household members, among others.

en_name: Women Business and the Law Index Score (scale 1-100)
en_description: The index measures how laws and regulations affect women¡¯s economic opportunity. Overall scores are calculated by taking the average score of each index (Mobility, Workplace, Pay, Marriage, Parenthood, Entrepreneurship, Assets and Pension), with 100 representing the highest possible score.

en_name: Proportion of seats held by women in national parliaments (%)
en_description: Women in parliaments are the percentage of parliamentary seats in a single or lower chamber held by women.

en_name: Women making their own informed decisions regarding sexual relations, contraceptive use and reproductive health care (% of women age 15-49)
en_description: Proportion of women ages 15-49 years (married or in union) who make their own decision on all three selected areas i.e. can say no to sexual intercourse with their husband or partner if they do not want; decide on use of contraception; and decide on their own health care. Only women who provide a ¡°yes¡± answer to all three components are considered as women who ¡°make her own decisions regarding sexual and reproductive¡±.

en_name: Women participating in the three decisions (own health care, major household purchases, and visiting family) (% of women age 15-49)
en_description: Women participating in the three decisions (own health care, major household purchases, and visiting family) is the percentage of currently married women aged 15-49 who say that they alone or jointly have the final say in all of the three decisions (own health care, large purchases and visits to family, relatives, and friends).

en_name: School enrollment, tertiary, male (% gross)
en_description: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Tertiary education, whether or not to an advanced research qualification, normally requires, as a minimum condition of admission, the successful completion of education at the secondary level.

en_name: School enrollment, tertiary, female (% gross)
en_description: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Tertiary education, whether or not to an advanced research qualification, normally requires, as a minimum condition of admission, the successful completion of education at the secondary level.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed short-cycle tertiary, population 25+, total (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed short-cycle tertiary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed short-cycle tertiary, population 25+, male (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed short-cycle tertiary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed short-cycle tertiary, population 25+, female (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed short-cycle tertiary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least Master's or equivalent, population 25+, total (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed Master's or equivalent.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least Master's or equivalent, population 25+, male (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed Master's or equivalent.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least Master's or equivalent, population 25+, female (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed Master's or equivalent.

en_name: Educational attainment, Doctoral or equivalent, population 25+, total (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed Doctoral or equivalent.

en_name: Educational attainment, Doctoral or equivalent, population 25+, male (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed Doctoral or equivalent.

en_name: Educational attainment, Doctoral or equivalent, population 25+, female (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed Doctoral or equivalent.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least Bachelor's or equivalent, population 25+, total (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed Bachelor's or equivalent.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least Bachelor's or equivalent, population 25+, male (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed Bachelor's or equivalent.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least Bachelor's or equivalent, population 25+, female (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed Bachelor's or equivalent.

en_name: Secondary education, teachers (% female)
en_description: Female teachers as a percentage of total secondary education teachers includes full-time and part-time teachers.

en_name: Progression to secondary school, male (%)
en_description: Progression to secondary school refers to the number of new entrants to the first grade of secondary school in a given year as a percentage of the number of students enrolled in the final grade of primary school in the previous year (minus the number of repeaters from the last grade of primary education in the given year).

en_name: Progression to secondary school, female (%)
en_description: Progression to secondary school refers to the number of new entrants to the first grade of secondary school in a given year as a percentage of the number of students enrolled in the final grade of primary school in the previous year (minus the number of repeaters from the last grade of primary education in the given year).

en_name: School enrollment, secondary, male (% net)
en_description: Net enrollment rate is the ratio of children of official school age who are enrolled in school to the population of the corresponding official school age. Secondary education completes the provision of basic education that began at the primary level, and aims at laying the foundations for lifelong learning and human development, by offering more subject- or skill-oriented instruction using more specialized teachers.

en_name: School enrollment, secondary, female (% net)
en_description: Net enrollment rate is the ratio of children of official school age who are enrolled in school to the population of the corresponding official school age. Secondary education completes the provision of basic education that began at the primary level, and aims at laying the foundations for lifelong learning and human development, by offering more subject- or skill-oriented instruction using more specialized teachers.

en_name: School enrollment, secondary, male (% gross)
en_description: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Secondary education completes the provision of basic education that began at the primary level, and aims at laying the foundations for lifelong learning and human development, by offering more subject- or skill-oriented instruction using more specialized teachers.

en_name: School enrollment, secondary, female (% gross)
en_description: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Secondary education completes the provision of basic education that began at the primary level, and aims at laying the foundations for lifelong learning and human development, by offering more subject- or skill-oriented instruction using more specialized teachers.

en_name: Secondary education, vocational pupils (% female)
en_description: Secondary vocational pupils are the number of secondary students enrolled in technical and vocational education programs, including teacher training.

en_name: Secondary education, general pupils (% female)
en_description: Secondary general pupils are the number of secondary students enrolled in general education programs, including teacher training.

en_name: Secondary education, pupils (% female)
en_description: Female pupils as a percentage of total pupils at secondary level includes enrollments in public and private schools.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed upper secondary, population 25+, total (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed upper secondary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed upper secondary, population 25+, male (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed upper secondary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed upper secondary, population 25+, female (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed upper secondary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed post-secondary, population 25+, total (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed post-secondary non-tertiary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed post-secondary, population 25+, male (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed post-secondary non-tertiary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed post-secondary, population 25+, female (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed post-secondary non-tertiary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed lower secondary, population 25+, total (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed lower secondary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed lower secondary, population 25+, male (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed lower secondary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed lower secondary, population 25+, female (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed lower secondary education.

en_name: Children out of school, primary, male
en_description: Children out of school are the number of primary-school-age children not enrolled in primary or secondary school.

en_name: Children out of school, primary, female
en_description: Children out of school are the number of primary-school-age children not enrolled in primary or secondary school.

en_name: Adjusted net enrollment rate, primary, male (% of primary school age children)
en_description: Adjusted net enrollment is the number of pupils of the school-age group for primary education, enrolled either in primary or secondary education, expressed as a percentage of the total population in that age group.

en_name: Adjusted net enrollment rate, primary, female (% of primary school age children)
en_description: Adjusted net enrollment is the number of pupils of the school-age group for primary education, enrolled either in primary or secondary education, expressed as a percentage of the total population in that age group.

en_name: Primary education, teachers (% female)
en_description: Female teachers as a percentage of total primary education teachers includes full-time and part-time teachers.

en_name: Trained teachers in primary education, male (% of male teachers)
en_description: Trained teachers in primary education are the percentage of primary school teachers who have received the minimum organized teacher training (pre-service or in-service) required for teaching in a given country.

en_name: Trained teachers in primary education, female (% of female teachers)
en_description: Trained teachers in primary education are the percentage of primary school teachers who have received the minimum organized teacher training (pre-service or in-service) required for teaching in a given country.

en_name: Repeaters, primary, male (% of male enrollment)
en_description: Repeaters in primary school are the number of students enrolled in the same grade as in the previous year, as a percentage of all students enrolled in primary school.

en_name: Repeaters, primary, female (% of female enrollment)
en_description: Repeaters in primary school are the number of students enrolled in the same grade as in the previous year, as a percentage of all students enrolled in primary school.

en_name: Persistence to last grade of primary, male (% of cohort)
en_description: Persistence to last grade of primary is the percentage of children enrolled in the first grade of primary school who eventually reach the last grade of primary education. The estimate is based on the reconstructed cohort method.

en_name: Persistence to last grade of primary, female (% of cohort)
en_description: Persistence to last grade of primary is the percentage of children enrolled in the first grade of primary school who eventually reach the last grade of primary education. The estimate is based on the reconstructed cohort method.

en_name: Persistence to grade 5, male (% of cohort)
en_description: Persistence to grade 5 (percentage of cohort reaching grade 5) is the share of children enrolled in the first grade of primary school who eventually reach grade 5. The estimate is based on the reconstructed cohort method.

en_name: Persistence to grade 5, female (% of cohort)
en_description: Persistence to grade 5 (percentage of cohort reaching grade 5) is the share of children enrolled in the first grade of primary school who eventually reach grade 5. The estimate is based on the reconstructed cohort method.

en_name: Net intake rate in grade 1, male (% of official school-age population)
en_description: Net intake rate in grade 1 is the number of new entrants in the first grade of primary education who are of official primary school entrance age, expressed as a percentage of the population of the corresponding age.

en_name: Net intake rate in grade 1, female (% of official school-age population)
en_description: Net intake rate in grade 1 is the number of new entrants in the first grade of primary education who are of official primary school entrance age, expressed as a percentage of the population of the corresponding age.

en_name: School enrollment, primary, male (% net)
en_description: Net enrollment rate is the ratio of children of official school age who are enrolled in school to the population of the corresponding official school age. Primary education provides children with basic reading, writing, and mathematics skills along with an elementary understanding of such subjects as history, geography, natural science, social science, art, and music.

en_name: School enrollment, primary, female (% net)
en_description: Net enrollment rate is the ratio of children of official school age who are enrolled in school to the population of the corresponding official school age. Primary education provides children with basic reading, writing, and mathematics skills along with an elementary understanding of such subjects as history, geography, natural science, social science, art, and music.

en_name: Gross intake ratio in first grade of primary education, male (% of relevant age group)
en_description: Gross intake ratio in first grade of primary education is the number of new entrants in the first grade of primary education regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the population of the official primary entrance age.

en_name: Gross intake ratio in first grade of primary education, female (% of relevant age group)
en_description: Gross intake ratio in first grade of primary education is the number of new entrants in the first grade of primary education regardless of age, expressed as a percentage of the population of the official primary entrance age.

en_name: School enrollment, primary, male (% gross)
en_description: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Primary education provides children with basic reading, writing, and mathematics skills along with an elementary understanding of such subjects as history, geography, natural science, social science, art, and music.

en_name: School enrollment, primary, female (% gross)
en_description: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Primary education provides children with basic reading, writing, and mathematics skills along with an elementary understanding of such subjects as history, geography, natural science, social science, art, and music.

en_name: Primary education, pupils (% female)
en_description: Female pupils as a percentage of total pupils at primary level include enrollments in public and private schools.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed primary, population 25+ years, total (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed primary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed primary, population 25+ years, male (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed primary education.

en_name: Educational attainment, at least completed primary, population 25+ years, female (%) (cumulative)
en_description: The percentage of population ages 25 and over that attained or completed primary education.

en_name: Primary completion rate, male (% of relevant age group)
en_description: Primary completion rate, or gross intake ratio to the last grade of primary education, is the number of new entrants (enrollments minus repeaters) in the last grade of primary education, regardless of age, divided by the population at the entrance age for the last grade of primary education. Data limitations preclude adjusting for students who drop out during the final year of primary education.

en_name: Primary completion rate, female (% of relevant age group)
en_description: Primary completion rate, or gross intake ratio to the last grade of primary education, is the number of new entrants (enrollments minus repeaters) in the last grade of primary education, regardless of age, divided by the population at the entrance age for the last grade of primary education. Data limitations preclude adjusting for students who drop out during the final year of primary education.

en_name: School enrollment, preprimary, male (% gross)
en_description: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Preprimary education refers to programs at the initial stage of organized instruction, designed primarily to introduce very young children to a school-type environment and to provide a bridge between home and school.

en_name: School enrollment, preprimary, female (% gross)
en_description: Gross enrollment ratio is the ratio of total enrollment, regardless of age, to the population of the age group that officially corresponds to the level of education shown. Preprimary education refers to programs at the initial stage of organized instruction, designed primarily to introduce very young children to a school-type environment and to provide a bridge between home and school.

en_name: School enrollment, tertiary (gross), gender parity index (GPI)
en_description: Gender parity index for gross enrollment ratio in tertiary education is the ratio of women to men enrolled at tertiary level in public and private schools.

en_name: School enrollment, secondary (gross), gender parity index (GPI)
en_description: Gender parity index for gross enrollment ratio in secondary education is the ratio of girls to boys enrolled at secondary level in public and private schools.

en_name: School enrollment, primary and secondary (gross), gender parity index (GPI)
en_description: Gender parity index for gross enrollment ratio in primary and secondary education is the ratio of girls to boys enrolled at primary and secondary levels in public and private schools.

en_name: School enrollment, primary (gross), gender parity index (GPI)
en_description: Gender parity index for gross enrollment ratio in primary education is the ratio of girls to boys enrolled at primary level in public and private schools.

en_name: Literacy rate, adult male (% of males ages 15 and above)
en_description: Adult literacy rate is the percentage of people ages 15 and above who can both read and write with understanding a short simple statement about their everyday life.

en_name: Literacy rate, adult female (% of females ages 15 and above)
en_description: Adult literacy rate is the percentage of people ages 15 and above who can both read and write with understanding a short simple statement about their everyday life.

en_name: Literacy rate, youth male (% of males ages 15-24)
en_description: Youth literacy rate is the percentage of people ages 15-24 who can both read and write with understanding a short simple statement about their everyday life.

en_name: Literacy rate, youth (ages 15-24), gender parity index (GPI)
en_description: Gender parity index for youth literacy rate is the ratio of females to males ages 15-24 who can both read and write with understanding a short simple statement about their everyday life.

en_name: Literacy rate, youth female (% of females ages 15-24)
en_description: Youth literacy rate is the percentage of people ages 15-24 who can both read and write with understanding a short simple statement about their everyday life.

en_name: Firms with female participation in ownership (% of firms)
en_description: Firms with female participation in ownership are the percentage of firms with a woman among the principal owners.

en_name: Firms with female top manager (% of firms)
en_description: Firms with female top manager refers to the percentage of firms in the private sector who have females as top managers. Top manager refers to the highest ranking manager or CEO of the establishment. This person may be the owner if he/she works as the manager of the firm. The results are based on surveys of more than 100,000 private firms.
